<HEAD>With AM-Barriers Broken Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Sign Language No Snap Course</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elisabeth Ann Zinser, who resigned as
president of Gallaudet University amid protests from students who
want a deaf leader, enraged students and faculty at the school for
the hearing impaired by suggesting she would quickly learn sign
language.
   In truth, say professors at Gallaudet, learning sign language _
widely considered the nation's third most frequently used
``foreign'' language _ is as difficult as mastering Russian or
Chinese.
   ``She (Zinser) thought she would come in here and pick up sign
language in three months,'' said Robert Johnson, an audiology
professor at the nation's only liberal arts college for the hearing
impaired. ``Unfortunately, you don't catch sign like you catch a
cold.''
   There are three different varieties of sign language, the purest
of which has no connection with the English language, while the
crudest version relies heavily on English vocabulary and sentence
structure, Johnson said.
   Johnson and Scott Lidell, both professors in Gallaudet's
department of linguistics, say around 2 million Americans are
considered deaf by audiometric standards, while 18 million others
suffer from some hearing loss.
   Those who use sign language are usually in the smaller group,
while persons with less severe hearing loss do not usually learn
sign language. The majority of Gallaudet's students are profoundly
deaf, and use sign language, according to school officials.
   American Sign Language, the purest form of signing, is commonly
used between people who are either profoundly deaf, or have been
deaf since birth, Johnson said. Comparing ASL to the use of a
foreign language, ASL users are roughly equivalent to those fluent
in a foreign tongue.
   But similarities with written or spoken language end there,
Johnson emphasized.
   ``English relies on a linear structure, with one word following
the last, but in ASL, the message is conveyed through simultaneous
use of facial expressions, finger signs, and motions,'' Johnson
said.
   ASL has a base vocabulary on which general themes, not
individual words, are built. Images, rather than words expressed in
sign, convey the signer's message.
   ``It's extremely time-efficient,'' Lidell said. ``You have two
hands, a face, and a body participating in delivering the message.
In spoken or written English, you have just words. Signing gives
you more channels.''
   Deaf people comunicating with hearing people mix sign language
with some components of formal English, the result being a type of
sign language called Contact Variety Signing, or Pidgin Sign
English.
   In the Contact Variety method, the message expressed may use
numerous images associated with ASL, but the message is based on
the syntax of an English sentence.
   It is this form of communication through which Gallaudet student
protest leaders, with the assistance of interpreters, conveyed
their message to the media and campus onlookers.
   Sign Supported English is the third type of sign. It does not
rely on facial expressions, and involves sending messages primarily
with spoken English. Signing symbols are used to reinforce the
spoken message, in what Johnson describes as ``coding speech on the
hands.''
   Sign Supported English, Johnson said, is slow and awkward, and
is the only type of sign language Zinser could have learned in less
than six months. There are sign language symbols for each of the 26
characters in the English alphabet, and, when signers cannot find a
symbol for an English word, they may spell out the English word,
then return to sign. Fingerspelling is used in all three types of
sign.
   Gallaudet professors, 30 percent of whom are deaf, are required
to know sign language, and must pass sign examinations for
promotions or raises, according to Roger Beach, a counseling
professor who designed Gallaudet's exam program.
</TEXT>
