<HL> Letters to the Editor: Let's Swear Off Vulgar Language </HL>
<SO> </SO>
<TEXT>
   Re Robert Perrin's Sept. 27 editorial-page article "There's Too Darn Much Cussing in This Goshdang Society": I agree wholeheartedly with his contention that there is too much use of vulgar language in this country. 
In fact, I would go as far as to say that the amount of this vile talk is detrimental to our language as a whole, for it perverts the very fabric that makes up the English language. 

   By this I mean that the use of obscenities is almost always used in place of a more appropriate word that is not obscene and is better fitting. 
What we have so graciously called "four-letter words" are nothing more than a crutch for those who do not know how to use the English language correctly or those who do not want to use it correctly. 
In either case, I am afraid that we are cheapening our native tongue as well as robbing ourselves and our children of the opportunity to speak both eloquently and succinctly. 
This is a sad happening for all in our society and need not be. 

   Charles F. Edris
   Boca Raton, Fla.
   ---
   Three cheers for Mr. Perrin's article. 
I regret the increased incidence of "blue" language. 
I suppose every language has its expletives and they probably all relate -- people being people -- to the same body parts and functions. 
But these expletives should be reserved for occasions calling for a cuss. 
When they permeate all conversations, they lose their intrinsic value and our language is that much weaker. 

   People who believe language represents values have put up with this assault too long. 

   Robert Marquis
   Princeton, N.J. 

   ---
   I am so happy to see an article like this written by a man. 
Perhaps articles such as Mr. Perrin's will help to get across the message that profanity is just a sad excuse for a poor vocabulary. 

   Vera L. Proffitt
   Alcoa, Tenn.
</TEXT>
