<HEAD>On Premier's Orders, Language Guardians Do Some Finetuning</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUB 12th graf, `There will...' to replace dashes with
parenthesis to avoid garble.
^By ELAINE GANLEY</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The guardians of French, who spend much of their
time defending the purity of their mother tongue, have conceded it
contains ``absurdities, uncertainties and anomalies'' and issued 15
pages of spelling corrections.
   The government-requested overhaul proved that spelling is ``a
national psychodrama,'' the daily newspaper Liberation said.
   Premier Michel Rocard, who requested the spelling review last
year, on Tuesday accepted the changes submitted by the High Council
on the French Language. He ordered that the new spellings be taught
in all schools starting next year.
   He also ordered a meeting of dictionary specialists, publishing
houses, the press and all those dealing with the written word to
find the best way to make the new spellings the norm.
   ``It was never a question that the government legislate in such
matters. The language belongs to those who use it,'' Rocard said.
``But it is up to the government ... to favor that usage which
appears most satisfactory.''
   Anticipating a collective shudder from the citizenry, the High
Council offered reassurances. The new spellings would, for example,
change no more than two words on two full pages of Proust's ``La
Pleiade.''
   Small comfort to schoolchildren, parents and teachers, said an
association of university professors, who predicted that some words
would have two different spellings for years to come.
   ``Once again, students, parents and teachers will be disoriented
and finish by accepting no rules at all,'' said the Societe des
Agreges. ``Under the pretext of correcting fancied anomalies, new
ones are being introduced.''
   The High Council said it was not reforming the language, only
making ``certain rectifications of absurdities ... uncertainties
... and anomalies'' that ``troubled the experts themselves.''
   The five categories of changes affect the hyphen, accent marks,
the plural form of compound words, accordance of the past
participle in reflexive verbs and a potpourri of anomalies.
   The hyphen, much used in French, is going out of style,
according to the sages, who are all but discarding it. Even the
hyphen used in English words like ``cow-boy,'' ``strip-tease'' or
``week-end'' will disappear.
   There will be fewer circumflexes (
</TEXT>
<HEAD>) in the new French. The</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ``accent grave,'' the left to right slash above certain letters,
will be ``generalized,'' removing the many exceptions under which
it is applied.
   More drastic changes do away with the feminine ``e'' or plural
``s'' when according past participles with reflexive verbs _ in
certain cases. And the second half of compound words, when plural,
will always end in ``s,'' while the first half will lose the ``s.''
   The Academie Francaise, whose 40 ``immortals'' are the ultimate
arbiters of the French language, approved the changes, along with
the Councils of the French Language of the French Communities of
Belgium and Quebec.
   The French language has always been a reverent issue here, and
successive governments have tried to stamp out Anglicisms and other
impurities, sometimes resorting to fines for offenders.
   Last week, President Francois Mitterrand, a vociferous defender
of his mother tongue, complained that English was supplanting
French in the European Community.
   Mitterrand said ensuring the place of French as an official EC
language was a top priority of his government, and added that
France was prepared to help the EC ``enable its employees to
acquire the linguistic competence needed to perform their
missions.''
   But the university professors said the spelling changes would
defeat that cause.
   ``Once again, the error is being made that French is no longer a
universal language because it is too difficult. English has become
a spoken language around the world,'' the group said, ``despite the
fact that its spelling is unchanged and often without logic.''
</TEXT>
