<HEAD>Presidential Campaign Provides Slim Pickings For Dictionary Makers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRUDY TYNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This year's presidential campaign
between Republican George Bush and Democrat Michael Dukakis has
made little contribution to the English language, say editors at
Merriam-Webster dictionaries.
   ``It's been dull,'' said senior editor James G. Lowe, whose
lexicographers have been keeping close tabs on campaign rhetoric in
hopes of finding new words.
   Since the days of ``caucus,'' an Algonquin Indian term that
entered the American political vocabulary in the 1760s, and down
through ``mugwump,'' ``power broker,'' ``suffragette,''
``smoke-filled rooms,'' ``arm-twisting,'' ``wheeler-dealer'' and
``dirty tricks,'' national politics and particularily presidential
campaigns have been a rich source of new words, he said.
   Although the candidates have revived some old terms, such as
``limousine liberal,'' coined by Mario Procaccino during his 1969
campaign against New York City Mayor John Lindsay, they have come
up with little new.
   With only a few weeks of the campaign left, Lowe sees only
``scam'' used as a combining term _ as in ``Iranscam,''
``Contrascam,'' ``debatescam'' _ as enduring and ``pastel
patriotism'' as a possible starter.
   According to one version, ``pastel patriots'' were what the
Republicans called the Democrats for decorating their convention
arena not in traditional red, white and blue but in hues that
looked red, white and blue on television.
   ``I don't know whether to blame their speech writers, but the
candidates haven't been talking about issues,'' said Lowe, pointing
out that this campaign is devoid of New Deals, Square Deals,
Hoovervilles and frontiers of any kind.
   ``Their forte is one-liners,'' he said. ``It's a quick way of
getting attention, but as soon as the campaign is over those
one-liners will be forgotten.''
   Even the press has been uninspired, according to Lowe.
   ``It's very often the journalists that invent words,'' Lowe
said. ``Time and Newsweek magazines, because of their breezy style
and need to condense information, have been particularily fertile
sources for us over the years. But not in this campaign.''
   A new word gets into Webster's simply by being used repeatedly
in newspapers, magazines and other contemporary writing. Lowe's
staff spends most of its time reading and noting new words and new
uses on citation cards, and when a term builds up sufficient
citations over an extended period of time, it is added to the
dictionary.
   The test involves being more than a one-campaign phenomenon,
such as former Vice President Spiro Agnew's ``radiclib,'' which
quickly amassed a pile of citations following his 1970 speech and
has been heard little since.
   The Reagan years in general have provided slim linguistic
pickings, Lowe said. Two terms that have stuck and moved beyond
their political origins are ``exit poll,'' which came into popular
use in 1980 when West Coast television viewers learned before their
polls closed that Reagan had defeated Jimmy Carter, and ``yuppy,''
which blossomed with Colorado Sen. Gary Hart's campaign for the
Democratic nomination in 1984.
   Not only has the current crop of candidates added little to the
vocabulary, Republican vice presidential hopeful Dan Quayle even
tried, unsuccessfully, to get Webster's to delete a word.
   Quayle took offense last year at supplementary definitions for
the word ``hoosier'' in the Third New International Dictionary,
which pointed out that besides referring to a resident of Indiana,
the noun can refer to an ``awkward, unhandy or unskilled person.''
As a verb the word can mean ``to loaf or botch a job.''
   Quayle suggested the dictionary company define ``hoosier'' as
``someone who is quick, smart, resourceful, skillful, a winner.''
   William A. Llewellyn, president of Merriam-Webster, declined to
revise the dictionary entry. He pointed out that many words have
more than one meaning and ``we in the dictionary business cannot
arbitrarily decide that we will enter only one of those senses.''
   ``Dictionary makers do not truly define words,'' Llewellyn said.
``Rather, they record the language as it is used.''
</TEXT>
