<LEADPARA>  Cristalina Cendejas, a student at Sequoia High School in Redwood City, has a
hard time putting her thoughts into words -- when the words are spoken in
English.;   This smart teen-ager who emigrated from Mexico last year is
learning English in the school's program for students with limited English
proficiency.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Peninsula Extra  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  MOTIVATED YET STRUGGLING
ENGLISH POSES BIG BARRIER TO NON-NATIVE SPEAKERS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Also ran in EAST5, EX3/9, EX4/4  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Although her spoken English is limited, her intelligence and energy are
not. In a detailed poster, Cristalina analyzed the political and economic
causes of the Colonial Revolution to the point of poetic metaphor for a U.S.
history class assignment.;   For a student with only limited English to have
the analytical skills to liken the British Empire to a sick, then dying man
losing his grip on his surroundings, and to do it in English, does not
surprise guidance counselor Karen Ramirez.;   "We get a good number, of
students who come with skills and motivation, but no English language skills,"
Ramirez said. "Because they can't read English doesn't mean they can't
think.";   Sequoia's English proficiency program, chaired by Joan Green, has
been struggling with the question of how to motivate and interest these kids
while teaching them basic language skills since 1978. They think they've
arrived at a solution with their sheltered studies program.;   "The one huge
dilemma schools have to agonize over is: Do you immerse them at the expense of
learning or do you give them a so-called "sheltered" bilingual program where
you give them studies and hope they learn the language?" Green said.;   Just
learning a language isn't very challenging, Green said. And kids who aren't
challenged are kids who get bored and lose interest in school. "We want to
keep them on track with their peers and we want to keep them in school," Green
said.;   At Sequoia, kids learn English by studying social studies, science
and mathematics. The materials -- books, lectures, slides and classroom
assignments -- are in English.;   But discussions and reinforcement are in
Spanish as often as they are in English.;   "The hardest part about learning a
language is expressing yourself in it," Green said. "Here they may comprehend
the material and they can feel competent and successful and they can move
ahead.";   Most of the students in the program are Latino, Green said. But
they reach many Vietnamese, as well as the occasional Russian, Bulgarian and
Chinese student.;   "It's tougher for the kids who don't speak either Spanish
or English," she said. "For them, it nearly is an immersion program.";   But
funny things happen. "Last year, we had Vietnamese students who learned
Spanish as well as English -- and the other kids learned a few words of
Vietnamese," Green said.;   Current research shows it takes four to seven
years to learn a language well enough to be able to talk about tough concepts
in it, Green said.;   "The intent is to maximize their learning potential and
keep them on track with their peers and still provide a lot of English
language instruction -- and provide bilingual support and expression," she
said.;   So Sequoia's program teaches the kids world geography in the ninth
grade, world culture in the 10th, U.S. history in the 11th and government and
economics in the 12th.;   Those classes are taught over a double class period
by one teacher, who works on language as much as content. The kids chart
history, act out events and set up economic systems to enhance their
comprehension of the English language texts and discussions.;   "Once you've
felt the tax collector come and take your money when you have nothing to say
about it, you understand the idea of taxation without representation," Green
said.;   "It does not mean simplifying content or important concepts," she
said. "It means taking those important concepts out of the language they're
embedded in.";   The students also study math, science and, of course,
grammar. In those classes, they usually have bilingual teachers or teachers'
aides, Green said.;   "These kids want to go to college so we have to teach
them on a high enough level that they can aim for it," Green said.  </TEXT>
