<HEAD>Committee Calls For New Standards For English Teaching</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The birthplace of English had better mind its p's
and q's and improve its English teaching methods at the same time,
according to a government study which criticizes how the language
is taught in Great Britain.
   The study, released Friday by a government-appointed committee,
concluded that most English teachers in Britain were not properly
equipped for the job and recommended that many be retrained.
   Education Secretary Kenneth Baker welcomed the report. He said
his department will incorporate its recommendations into a new
curriculum planned by Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's
Conservative government in a major shake-up of the nation's
educational system.
   ``Most schools no longer teach old-fashioned grammar. But little
has been put in its place,'' Baker said last year when he
established the committee to study the situation.
   The 90-page report follows a yearlong inquiry by the committee
into how English is taught in Britain. Panel members include Peter
Levi, professor of poetry at Oxford University; novelists Antonia
Byatt and Keith Waterhouse; broadcaster Robert Robinson; and poet
P.J. Kavanagh. They visited schools across the nation before
writing the report.
   The report says all teachers should be trained in English and
that each school should have a teacher whose sole job is to ensure
that the language is used properly.
   It adds that national standards should be established to be met
by children at the ages of seven, 11 and 16. However, the committee
rejected a return to memorizing grammar rules.
   ``We're not anxious to go back to the idea that you simply learn
these things by rote, because all the evidence is that that doesn't
in fact improve the effectiveness of the children's use of the
language,'' said Sir John Kingman, vice-chancellor of Bristol
University and head of the committee.
   Kingman rejected the notion that the new standards would
discriminate against pupils from ethnic minority groups.
   Of Britain's 56 million people, about 2.45 million are
non-whites, mostly immigrants from Asia, Africa and the Caribbean
whose children were born and raised in Britain.
   ``The fact that they may speak a different language at home is
irrelevant, because the English language is the way they become
full members of English society,'' Kingman said.
   ``It is a way of ensuring that we do not have an underclass of
non-English speakers who are cut off from getting a job and having
a career.''
   The opposition Labor Party and the 184,400-member National Union
of Teachers also welcomed the report.
   But Michael Simon, head of the Inner London Education
Authority's English Center, said he was concerned about the notion
that all pupils must conform to a standard form of English.
   ``About 80 percent of pupils do not speak standard English
although they speak something very close to it. Any attempt to get
kids to speak standard English will just disable them as
speakers,'' he said.
   Kingman, a mathematician, said English teachers were not being
trained well in Britain and that children were suffering.
   ``We take a fairly dim view of English teacher training,'' he
said.
   The report said that by age 7, children should read passages of
simple sentences, understand the spoken language, spell common
words and write legibly; by 11, they should use punctuation and
paragraphs, argue their case on an issue and be aware of dialects.
   It said 16-year-olds should be able to express feelings, ideas
and arguments in writing and speech, make comparisions between
English and other languages and use technical terms to describe
language.
   English is the first language of 320 million people around the
world and is spoken daily by about a billion people.
