<TEXT>     The erudite senator recently told his colleagues that he wanted to make the
longest word in English by taking the term "floccinaucinihilipilification" and
adding the suffix "-ism.";    Flocci-etc., first used in 1741, means the
action or habit of estimating everything as worthless, and at 29 letters, was
the longest word in the Oxford English Dictionary, First Edition.;    But in
an editorial Wednesday, the New York Times noted that Moynihan's 32-letter
coinage isn't long enough to break the record.;    "It appears, alas, that the
senator hasn't consulted a big dictionary for quite a while," the Times
crowed. "Since 1961, the longest word in the unabridged Merriam-Webster Third
New International Dictionary has been 'pneumonoultram-
icroscopicsilicovolcanoconiosis' -- 45 letters -- a made-up word describing a
lung disease caused by breathing volcanic or other fine dust.";    A writer
named F. Scully coined that word in a 1936 book titled "Bedside Manna,"
according to the Times.;    Even the literate newspaper of record neglected to
mention, however, the longest word ever to appear in literature. It is found
in "The Ecclesiaszusae," a comedy by Aristophanes.;    In Greek, the word has
170 letters but when transliterated into the Roman alphabet, it has 182 (don't
bother counting them -- we didn't).;    The term --
lopadotemachoselachogaleokran-ioleipsanodrimhypotrimmatosilphiopa
raomeli-tokatakechymenokichlepikossyphophattoperister-alektryonoptekephalliokig
 lopeleiolagoiosira-iobaphetraganopterygon -- describes a fricassee of 17
