<LEADPARA>  DICTIONARIES -- big, fat, gray and boring -- used to be the place to look up
words longer than a Lincoln Town Car, the kind of 25-cent terms that impress
the elbow-patch set.;    But open the pages of the just-published Random House
Webster's College Dictionary and you're likely to find words like "mall-rat,"
"touchy-feely," "airkiss" and "boy toy."  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  NEW DICTIONARY OPEN TO SLANG AND SENSITIVITIES  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Language  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Heavens. What would Shakespeare think?;    It doesn't matter. Language --
especially American English -- changes with the times, and dictionaries mark
those changes.;    "Shakespeare didn't know any rules, he just followed his
own language," said Sol Steinmetz, executive editor of Random House
dictionaries.;    We've come a long way, baby. Random House touts its new
dictionary as being "gender neutral," meaning it avoids sexist definitions and
advises against using certain offensive words.;    "As we watched the language
change over the past 20 years, there has been a change in the consciousness of
people as far as sexism," Steinmetz said.;    Some dictionaries define
chairwoman as "a woman acting as a chairman." Random House defines the word as
a woman who heads a meeting or committee. And they spell it two ways: women
and the alternate "womyn," which separates the men from the women.;    This is
murky stuff. Jonathan Latimer, a publisher at Houghton-Mifflin, which prints
the American Heritage Dictionary, said he was surprised at Random House's
emphasis on being "politically correct.";    The American Heritage suggests
word usage but does not weigh in on sexism as strongly as Random House.;   
"It is true that sensitivities have grown more acute in certain areas,"
Latimer said. "It is more complex than that. You have to be very careful how
you label things.";    Steinmetz said the new Random House Webster's was
edited "on line," meaning that the whole dictionary was on computer before it
went to press.;    So when world events happened inconveniently, there was
time to fit them in. The reunification of Germany, for example, forced the
rewriting of 318 entries.;    Real life is tough on dictionaries. "Teflon,"
for example, has a new definition, spawned by the term "Teflon president." The
non-stick cookware coating now also is defined as "characterized by
imperviousness to blame or criticism.";    What's going on here?;    It's
progress.;    What do you do when someone invents a machine that dispenses
cash at the touch of a button? Well, you have to call it something, and
"automatic teller machine" now is an entry in the Random House dictionary.;   
"It would be silly to think that language would not change," said Haig
Der-Houssikian, a social linguist at the University of Florida. "Anyone who
stands in the way is fighting nature."  </TEXT>
